This paper is about evaluating semantic textual similarity (STS) systems, which is a subfield of natural language processing (NLP) and computational linguistics (CL). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of machine learning models such as Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA), Word2Vec, and UMBC Ebiquity, which are commonly used in artificial intelligence (AI) and machine learning (ML) research, making cs.AI a likely sub-category as well. The paper also involves statistical analysis and modeling, which falls under the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning). Information retrieval (IR) is also relevant as the paper discusses the comparison of different STS models. Finally, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is a less likely sub-category, but it is possible that the paper discusses the computational complexity of the STS models or the human judgments collected.
